gs":["English:  see  Peart  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peart","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Perth (Perths), which is recorded as <i>Pert</i><i>c.</i> 1128. The placename derives from Pictish <i>perta</i> ‘(at the) thicket, copse’.","English: nickname, probably from a shortened form of Middle English, Old French <i>apert</i> ‘open, plain to see’, of persons ‘frank, honest’ or ‘accomplished’."]}]},{"name":"bzw.","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Berkshire and Oxfordshire): from Middle English <i>be(a)u</i>, <i>bewe</i> ‘beautiful, fair’ (Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Bugh","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Bew  . This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Ferrette","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Adrien, Alcee, Anite, Emile, Emilien, Jean-Louis, Rosaire.","Variant of   Verrett  , a surname of French origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Verrett","meanings":["Altered form of French   Verret  , reflecting the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."]}]},{"name":"Hilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic origin, a Latinized short form of any of several girls' names derived from <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. Many of these are found in both Continental Germanic and Old English forms.  St Hilda  (  614–80 ) was a Northumbrian princess who founded the abbey at Whitby and became its abbess. The name all but died out by the 14th century. It was strongly revived in the 19th century. Since the 1930s, however, it has again fallen from favour."],"variants":[{"name":"Hylda","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Hilda ."]}]},{"name":"bzw.","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Berkshire and Oxfordshire): from Middle English <i>be(a)u</i>, <i>bewe</i> ‘beautiful, fair’ (Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Bugh","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."]}]},{"name":"Ita","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Íde ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hilda bzw. Ita von Pfirt bzw. Ferrette was born in 1085, in Ferrette, Haut-Rhin, Alsace, France, her father, Rudolf von Ferrette, was 35 and her mother, Irmintrud de Bar, was 33. She married Otto II. Graf von Habsburg about 1091, in Habsburg, Aargau, Switzerland. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1134, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1085–1134":"1085–1134","1057–1112":"1057–1112","1092–1134":"1092–1134","1102–1167":"1102–1167","1050–Male":"1050–Surnud","1052–1105":"1052–1105","about 1091":"umbes